Azerbaijan Plans to Reduce Investment Spending 17% This Year

-- B y   Z u l f u g a r   A g a y e v
-- 
2011-02-23T15:09:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-23/azerbaijan-plans-to-reduce-investment-spending-17-this-year.html
  Azerbaijan  plans to spend $4.3
billion on state investment projects this year, a 17 percent
decline on last year’s $5.2 billion, according to a document
seen by Bloomberg News.  Transportation projects will account for $1.1 billion of
the State Investment Program approved by the government on Jan.
26. A copy of the document, which has yet to be made public by
the government, was provided by the Public Union for Support to
Free Economy, an economic research group based in the capital,
Baku, that’s funded by the U.S. and British embassies among
others.  Projects include an airport in the northern region of
Gabala, which hosts a Russian radar station, at an estimated
cost of $100 million. The government aims to spend $63 million
on a new port in Baku.  The government will also allocate an additional $110
million for the construction of a cultural center in Baku in
honor of former President Heydar Aliyev, the father of the
country’s current leader, Ilham Aliyev. The center, designed by  Zaha Hadid , has cost $216 million since its construction started
in 2007.  A spokesman for Azerbaijan’s Cabinet, Akif Ali, had no
comment when contacted by telephone today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
